In this posting:
[1] Oneida County
[2] Oswego County

******
[1] Oneida County
Date: Sun 14 Sep 2014
Source: WAMC Northeast Public Radio [edited]
http://wamc.org/post/horse-cny-euthanized-eee-blamed


A horse in central New York has been euthanized after suffering with neurological signs associated with eastern equine encephalitis (EEE).

The disease is considered one of the most serious mosquito-borne virus [infections], and horses are almost always killed by it. The animal in the Town of Trenton [Oneida County] was put down last Monday [8 Sep 2014].

The New York state health department recommends that horses be vaccinated for the disease. In humans, it can produce symptoms ranging from mild flu-like illness to inflammation of the brain, coma, and death in about a third of those affected.

Currently, there is no vaccine for humans.

Oneida County health officials tell The Oneida Daily Dispatch they've been routinely testing mosquito pools in western sections of the county but had seen no positive specimens.

[Byline: Jim Levulis]

